58th Templar Of Bristlebane<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uaniar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aniar</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.docsmooth.com/images/dot.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/26/01 2:23:37 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.docsmooth.com/images/me.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Adding up the improvements</span><hr size=1> Sollwin:<br>
Quote:<br>
 Each cast has a 7% chance to Crit. This chance is calculated on each cast independantly of the other and will never &quot;add up&quot; to any set percentage in increased damage output over a givin time.<br>
<br>
It is possible, however inprobable, that you could cast all crits for a 30 min period. The odds against that are staggering, but nothing in the game limits the amount of crits you can have in a givin amount of time, it's all luck and random numbers.<br>
<br>
/quote<br>
You had it right in the first paragraph, then got confused.  I failed a test because of this: the odds of getting 100 crits in a row are 7%.  The odds of gettin 0 crits of 100 is 93%  (the chance of a single failure is 93%).  The way probability of a single occurance DOES NOT ADD UP, NOR MULTIPLY ACROSS MULTIPLE POSSIBILITIES.  Each chance is 7%.  The next chance is 7%.  The chance for both is 7%, not 14%, not 0.49%.  No, this doesn't make sense in ANY form of math, because it's probability - which is a league all it's own.<br>
<br>
My point is that probability for one occurance has NOTHING to do with multiple occurances.  You can say &quot;I averaged 12% crits in the last 8 casts&quot;, but not &quot;my chance for a crit is 12% over 8 casts&quot;, because it's still 7% FOR EACH CAST.<br>
<br>
Please stop trying to spread this 7% from a per-occurance number to a &quot;per-occurances&quot; number. <p><br>Aniar Orrenson
